Sometimes when athletes try to hit harder they use a lot more arm. The arm is definitely a part of generating force and we need it, but it also transfers force from previous actions! 

This is a reminder of the reverse s curve pattern in the shoulder/torso action where the majority of force is developed. If the athlete doesn't know how to use their hips and shoulders 👉 in sequence 👈 , then they'll end up relying on their arm producing less power. Each part of the sequence overlaps and transfers the force into the next part, ultimately leading to going through the ball. So each part needs separation and patience. The reverse S curve is simple the path most shoulders and armswings take to use the sequence and body optimally. Side bend + rotate back (pull back), rotate forward + side bend the other way (backward-forward-circular rotation). This allows us to reach high, puts our scapula in a good position and allows us to use the muscles around the arm/shoulder/torso optimally for hitting. We can generate and transfer the energy better, and develop strength overall and within this pattern to be better prepared.

For some this comes without thought through countless reps and exposure to various movements (baseball, basketball, dancing etc) that challenge the coordination in this way and were taught well. Others it takes mindful reps, mobility work and rewiring of how to move optimally for generating power. Every great hitter has this pattern at different levels, but its there.

I recommend all athletes that want to improve their hitting to RECORD themselves and see what they're actually doing. I have some tests in my feed that you can look at to see how your hips and shoulder separation is. From there its key to gradually get more separation and practice the movements in sequence, remembering what it feels like. This takes a lot of patience but it can be done. In BFV we train this pattern right from the beginning!

